  "prompt": "What happens to current account holders, how much money they can deposit in bank of old 500 1000 notes?",
  "response": "The details regarding the deposit of old \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes in bank accounts vary depending on the specific regulations and policies set by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) or the relevant central bank, especially in the context of demonetization events.\n\n### Key Points for Current Account Holders:\n1. **Deposit Limits**:  \n   During the 2016 demonetization in India, current account holders were allowed to deposit old \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes without any specific limit, as these accounts are typically used for business and commercial transactions. However, banks were required to monitor and report large or suspicious transactions to regulatory authorities.\n\n2. **KYC Compliance**:  \n   Current account holders must ensure their accounts are fully KYC (Know Your Customer) compliant. Non-KYC accounts may face restrictions on deposits.\n\n3. **Reporting Requirements**:  \n   Deposits beyond certain thresholds may trigger reporting to tax authorities. For example, large cash deposits could attract scrutiny under anti-money laundering laws.\n\n4. **Bank Policies**:  \n   Individual banks may have specific guidelines or restrictions in place. It is advisable to check with your bank for the latest updates and requirements.\n\n### Important Note:\nAs of October 2023, the \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes demonetized in 2016 are no longer legal tender in India and cannot be deposited. However, if there is a new demonetization event or policy change, the specifics would depend on the official announcements by the RBI or the government.\n\nAlways refer to the latest RBI guidelines or consult your bank for accurate and updated information.",
